{{distinguish|text=the Northern Cheyenne warrior Roman Nose, also known as [[Hook Nose]]}}
[[File:Roman Nose and wife.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Henry Roman Nose and wife]] [[Image:Henry Roman Nose.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Chief Roman Nose.]] Chief '''Henry Roman Nose''' (June 30, 1856 – June 12, 1917) was a highly respected [[Southern Cheyenne]] Chief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.american-tribes.com/Cheyenne/bio/HenryRomanNose.htm|author=|date=|title=Henry Roman Nose |publisher=American-Tribes.com|accessdate=2013-02-21}}</ref> Living during turbulent times, Roman Nose was recognized for facilitating a peaceful transition to a non-nomadic way of life, while retaining elements of his Cheyenne culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasr.net/travel/city.php?OK+watonga+chief-roman-nose&TravelTo=OK0603034&VA=Y&AttractionCategory=&Attraction_ID=OK0603034a012#.USa6Fhl5FYc|author=|date=|title=Chief Roman Nose|publisher=Leisure and Sports Review|accessdate=2013-02-21}}</ref> He was a vocal proponent of obtaining education and training.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ETr4OzPWqj0C&pg=PA116&dq=henry+roman+nose+speech&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZSQmUbnINY_c8ATem4DgDQ&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=henry%20roman%20nose%20speech&f=false|author=Hazel W. Hertzberg|title=The Search for an American Indian Identity: Modern Pan-Indian Movements|year=1971|publisher=Syracuse University Press|page=116}}</ref>
As a young warrior, Henry Roman Nose participated in the [[Red River War]]. After being captured, he was sent in 1878 to [[Fort_Marion#Second_United_States_period|Fort Marion]] in St. Augustine, Florida, where he was listed as a "ringleader".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drbronsontours.com/bronsonplainindiannames.html|author=Gil Wilson|date=|title=Names of Plain Indians Held at Fort Marion|publisher=Dr. Bronson and Friends: A History of the City of St. Augustine|accessdate=2013-02-21}}</ref> After release, he attended the [[Hampton_University#Native_Americans|Hampton Institute]] in Virginia and the [[Carlisle Indian Industrial School|Carlisle Institute]] in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hampton Normal and Agricultural Institute|title=Twenty-two Years' Work of the Hampton Normal and Agricultural Institute at Hampton, Virginia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NPmpwyk30gkC&pg=PA327&dq=Henry+Roman+Nose&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fgcmUabDPJDS9QStqIBY&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Henry%20Roman%20Nose&f=false|year=1893|publisher=Normal School Press|page=327}}</ref> In 1892, he received a land allotment in current-day [[Blaine County, Oklahoma]]. This land later became part of the [[Roman Nose State Park]], which was named in his honor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Boye|title=Holding Stone Hands: On the Trail of the Cheyenne Exodus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xojmsWaKJl4C&pg=PA336&dq=Henry+Roman+Nose&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fgcmUabDPJDS9QStqIBY&ved=0CE0Q6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Henry%20Roman%20Nose&f=false|year=2001|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|page=336}}</ref>
Henry Roman Nose died in 1917 in the canyon on which Roman Nose State Park was established.<ref>[http://getawaytips.azcentral.com/roman-nose-state-park-near-watonga-oklahoma-1221.html Jernigan, Meg "Roman Nose State Park Near Watonga, Oklahoma."] Retrieved March 20, 2014.</ref>
He is depicted in a mural, "Roman Nose Canyon", at [[United States Post Office Watonga]], painted by [[Edith Mahier]] in 1941.<ref name=nrhpdoc>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=09000213}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: United States Post Office Watonga |publisher=[[National Park Service]]|author=Alyson Greiner |date=July 19, 2007 |accessdate=April 27, 2017 }} With {{NRHP url|id=09000213|photos=y|title=14 photos, including multiple views of the mural}}.</ref>
